The start symbol S has only one production:

S → NT45 NT29

1. NT45 is a lexical rule.  
   NT45 can generate the terminal t2, so the very first symbol of any sentence derived from S must be t2.  
   That matches the first word of the string, so NT45 must be used for that word.

2. The remainder of the string (t7 t12 t6 t14 t6 t4 t11 t3) has to be generated by NT29.

   NT29 has only four productions:

   • NT29 → 't5' (1 word)  
   • NT29 → 't1' (1 word)  
   • NT29 → NT41 NT35 (2 constituents)  
   • NT29 → NT40 NT14 (2 constituents)

   It therefore cannot expand into more than two immediate constituents unless those constituents later expand further.

   – The two lexical alternatives (‘t5’, ‘t1’) are single-word strings and are clearly too short (our remainder is eight words).

   – For NT29 → NT41 NT35  
     • NT35 is lexical and can produce only t7, t15, or t17 (one word).  
       The only place where a t7 occurs in the remaining substring is the very first word (the second word of the whole sentence).  
       Consequently NT35 would have to correspond to that second word, leaving NT41 to generate the seven-word tail t12 t6 t14 t6 t4 t11 t3.  
     • NT41, however, can begin only with t6, t7, t17, or t11 (t11 t2 when the rule NT41 → NT20 NT45 is used).  
       It can never start with t12.  
       Therefore NT41 cannot generate the required seven-word sequence starting with t12.  
       Hence NT29 → NT41 NT35 is impossible.

   – For NT29 → NT40 NT14  
     • NT40 begins with whatever NT22 produces; NT22 can begin only with t12 (if NT22 → 't12') or with t7/other symbols produced by NT16, NT1, etc.  
       Consequently the leftmost word produced by NT40 is never t7 — yet our remainder starts with t7.  
       Thus NT40 cannot account for the first word of the remainder, which rules out this alternative as well.

Since none of NT29’s productions can yield the eight-word suffix beginning with t7, NT29 cannot generate that suffix, and therefore S cannot generate the entire given string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol is  
S → NT45 NT29.

1. NT45 has only two terminal productions: NT45 → 't2' | 't11'.  
   Therefore every sentence generated by the grammar must begin with either t2 or t11.  
   The given string indeed begins with t2, so token 1 can be produced by NT45.

2. The remaining 32 tokens must all be produced by NT29.  
   NT29 has four possible productions:

   • NT29 → 't5' (1 token)  
   • NT29 → 't1' (1 token)  
   • NT29 → NT41 NT35  
   • NT29 → NT40 NT14  

   Since 32 tokens are still to be generated, only the two binary rules are relevant.

3. Case NT29 → NT41 NT35  
   NT35 is a single-terminal non-terminal (it can generate only t7, t15 or t17), so NT41 would have to generate the first 31 tokens of the suffix and start with t0.  
   But every derivation of NT41 ultimately begins with one of the terminals t7, t6, t17 or t5 (its only possible leading tokens: either directly, or after any number of left-recursive expansions NT41 → NT41 NT0).  
   Consequently NT41 can never start with t0, so this case is impossible.

4. Case NT29 → NT40 NT14  
   NT14 can generate either
     – one token (t3, t12, t14, or t17), or  
     – two tokens NT17 NT50, whose first token is t0, t13 or t1 and whose second token is t11, t10 or t8.

   Thus the last 1 or 2 tokens of the whole suffix must belong to NT14, and the token immediately before them must be supplied by NT45 (because NT40 → NT22 NT45 and NT45 is the second element).  
   But NT45 can only be t2 or t11, and in every possible 1- or 2-token choice for NT14 the preceding token in the given string is t16, t14 or t9—not t2 or t11.  
   Therefore no split of the 32-token suffix matches NT40 NT14.

Since neither NT29 → NT41 NT35 nor NT29 → NT40 NT14 can generate the needed 32-token sequence, NT29 cannot derive the remainder of the string.  
Hence S cannot derive the entire string.

No

The start symbol has just one rule

    S → NT45 NT29

NT45 can only produce one single terminal, ‘t2’ or ‘t11’.
Because the given string starts with ‘t2’, NT45 must be

    NT45 ⇒ ‘t2’

So every other token (39 of them) has to be generated by NT29.

NT29 has four possibilities:

    NT29 → ‘t5’               (1 token)
    NT29 → ‘t1’               (1 token)
    NT29 → NT41 NT35          (|NT35| = 1 token)
    NT29 → NT40 NT14

The first two rules are impossible (they give a one-token string, we need 39).

1.  NT29 → NT41 NT35  
    NT35 can only be ‘t7’, ‘t15’ or ‘t17’.  
    Therefore the very last symbol produced by NT29 would have to be
    one of those three tokens.  
    In the target string the 40-th (last) token is ‘t0’, so this branch
    is impossible.

2.  NT29 → NT40 NT14  
    NT40 always expands as

        NT40 → NT22 NT45,  NT45 ⇒ ‘t2’ or ‘t11’

    hence the last symbol of the NT40 part is necessarily ‘t2’ or ‘t11’.
    Looking at the 39-token tail we have only three places where ‘t2’ or
    ‘t11’ occur (positions 2, 17, 31 of that tail).  
    One must be the boundary between NT40 and NT14; the remainder
    (following that boundary) must be produced by NT14.

    NT14 has exactly one non-terminal rule:

        NT14 → NT17 NT50           (every derivation starts with NT17)

    Possible first tokens NT17 can generate are
    t0, t13, t16, t10, t6, t2, t18 – never t1 or t17.

    • boundary after position 2 → remaining tail starts with t0  
      (allowed) but must end with NT50.  
      For the whole 37-token suffix NT50 must end in ‘t0’.  
      That forces NT50 → NT37 NT8 with NT8 ⇒ ‘t0’, so NT37 must
      finish with ‘t10’.  
      Yet NT37 ends in NT30, and NT30 can never end in ‘t10’ (its only
      endings come from NT56, which can end in t9 or t17 but not t10).  
      Contradiction.

    • boundary after position 17 → remaining tail starts with t1.  
      NT14 cannot start with t1 (see the list of NT17 openings), so this
      boundary is impossible.

    • boundary after position 31 → remaining tail starts with t17.  
      Again NT14 cannot start with t17, so impossible.

    Hence the rule NT29 → NT40 NT14 cannot match the string either.

Because neither of the two composite rules for NT29 can generate the
required 39-token suffix, NT29 cannot produce it at all.  Consequently
S cannot derive the whole 40-token string.

Answer: No
